'''José Nicolás de Teresa y Miranda''' (August 23, 1850, [[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla, Mexico]] - January 11, 1902, in [[Vienna|Vienna, Austria]],)<ref>{{cite book |last=Ai Camp |first=Roderic|title=Mexican Political Biographies, 1884–1934 |year=1991|publisher= University of Texas |location=Austin, Texas|isbn=0-292-75119-2|ref=mexpol}}</ref> was a Mexican businessman and politician. His parents were [[Nicolás de Teresa y Sánchez Tamés]], founder of the [[Banco Mercantil Mexicano]], and [[Dolores Miranda Muñoz]], daughter of the vice-consul of Spain in Mexico.<ref>{{cite book |last=Marichal|first=Carlos|title=Empresarios españoles de ida y vuelta en el México porfiriano y en la España de la Restauración. El caso de Antonio Basagotti y Arteta, 1880-1910|year=|publisher=|journal=Amérique Latine Histoire et Mémoire. Les Cahiers ALHIM|number=17|url=https://alhim.revues.org/3178}}</ref> The family of José de Teresa supported financially [[Benito Juárez]] during the civil wars in Mexico between the liberal and conservative parties in the 19th century.
José de Teresa married María Luisa Romero Rubio on July 2, 1886,<ref>{{cite book |last= Paz, et. al. |title=Los hombres prominentes de México |year=1888|publisher= La Patria|location=Mexico|isbn=|ref=hombprom}}</ref> daughter of the famous politician [[Manuel Romero Rubio]] and sister-in-law of [[Porfirio Díaz]], who was the president of Mexico from 1876 to 1911. He became City Council of Mexico and Senator of [[Yucatan|Yucatán]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Ai Camp |first=Roderic|title=Mexican Political Biographies, 1884–1934 |year=1991|publisher= University of Texas |location=Austin, Texas|isbn=0-292-75119-2|ref=mexpol}}</ref>
José de Teresa was the first ambassador of Mexico in Austria when finally the diplomatic relations between the two countries were re-established after a long period of tensions following the execution of [[Maximilian of Habsburg|Maximilian I of Mexico]] in 1867 by hands of [[Benito Juárez|Benito Juarez]]. José de Teresa died in [[Vienna]], and some rumors interpreted it as the Austrian revenge for the murder of Maximiliano.
José de Teresa created the '''Centro Mercantil''', the first store to accept credit sales in Mexico.<ref>{{cite book |last= Bunker|first=Steven B. |title=Creating Mexican Consumer Culture in the Age of Porfirio Díaz |year=2012|publisher= University of New Mexico Press|location=New Mexico|isbn=|ref=consumer}}</ref> The building that José de Teresa commanded for the '''Centro Mercantil''' was constructed in [[Old Portal de Mercaderes (Mexico City)|Portal de Mercaderes]] and became the first in [[Art Nouveau]] style in Mexico. It now hosts the [[Grand Hotel of Mexico City]], one of the most luxurious hotels in Mexico City.
