{{Infobox person | name = Sarah Hildreth Butler | image = Sarah Hildreth Butler.jpg | caption = | birth_name = Sarah Jones Hildreth | birth_date = {{birth date|1816|8|17}} | birth_place = [[Dracut, Massachusetts]], United States | death_date = {{death date and age|1876|4|8|1816|8|17}} | death_place = [[Massachusetts]], U.S. | resting_place = [[Hildreth Cemetery#Hildreth Family Cemetery|Hildreth Cemetery]], [[Lowell, Massachusetts]] | occupation = Stage actress | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | relatives = | spouse = {{marriage|[[Benjamin Butler]]|May 16, 1844|}} |children = 4, including [[Blanche Butler Ames|Blanche]] }}
'''Sarah Hildreth Butler''' (born '''Sarah Jones Hildreth''', August 17, 1816 &ndash; April 8, 1876) was an American stage actress. She was the wife of [[Benjamin Butler (politician)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]], a Massachusetts lawyer, controversial Union general in the [[American Civil War]], and a United States [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] representing Massachusetts from 1867 to 1875 and again from 1877 to 1879.
==Life== Sarah Hildreth was born in [[Dracut, Massachusetts]], the daughter of Dr. Israel Hildreth, a noted physician of the [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]] area, and Dolly Jones. At sixteen, she went to Boston for formal training in dramatics, performing all over the country. On May 16, 1844, she married Benjamin Butler, then a rising lawyer, at Saint Anne's Episcopal Church in Lowell; she was 27, he 25. The Butlers would have four children, three surviving to adulthood: [[Blanche Butler Ames|Blanche]] (1847–1939), who would marry [[Adelbert Ames]]; Paul (1852–1918; their first son, also named Paul, had died in 1850 at the age of five); and Ben-Israel (1855–1881). She retired from stage performance after her marriage.
Her husband, Major General Benjamin Franklin Butler's business partners included Sarah's brother Fisher, and her brother-in-law, W. P. Webster.
===Death=== Sarah Hildreth Butler died on April 8, 1876, at the age of 59, and is buried at [[Hildreth Cemetery#Hildreth Family Cemetery|her family's private cemetery]] in Lowell.
