{{Refimprove|date=June 2016}}
The phrase '''sustainable industries''' is related to the development of [[industry|industrial]] processes in a [[sustainability|sustainable]] way.

== History ==
The earliest mention of the phrase "sustainable industries" appeared in 1990 in a story about a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] group [[Reforestation|reforesting]] a [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|tropical forest]] to help create sustainable industries for the local populace.<ref>Dietrich, Bill. "Our Troubled Earth – Japan." ''The Seattle Times.'' November 13, 1990. Page F-2.</ref>

Soon after, a study entitled “Jobs in a Sustainable Economy” by Michael Renner of the [[Worldwatch Institute]] was published, using the term "sustainable industries".<ref>Michael Renner, [http://www.worldwatch.org/node/886 “Jobs in a Sustainable Economy”]. Worldwatch Institute #104 (September 1991). {{ISBN|1-878071-05-X}}</ref> This 1991 report concluded, "Contrary to the jobs-versus-owls rhetoric that blames environmental restrictions for layoffs, the movement toward an environmentally sustainable [[World economy|global economy]] will create far more jobs than it eliminates. The chief reason: non-[[Pollution|polluting]], environmentally sustainable industries tend to be intrinsically more labour intensive and less resource intensive than traditional processes."  Among the features of sustainable industry offered in the paper were [[Efficient energy use|energy efficiency]], resource conservation to meet the needs of future generations, safe and skill-enhancing working conditions, [[Waste minimisation|low waste production]] processes, and the use of safe and environmentally compatible materials. Some of the benefits, however would be offset by higher prices (due to labor costs) and a theoretically larger population needed to perform the same amount of work, increasing the [[Agriculture|agricultural]] and other loads on the system.

In February 2003 the business magazine Sustainable Industries was first published, offering news and analysis of core industries such as [[clean energy]] and [[green building]]. By 2012 the company had expanded to include digital media and event production with the Sustainable Industries Economic Forum in the U.S. Sustainable Industries merged with Triple Pundit in 2011.<ref>"[http://www.triplepundit.com/2011/10/triplepundit-sustainable-industries/ Big News: TriplePundit.com and Sustainable Industries Merge]" Triple Pundit, Oct. 20, 2011</ref> Then in 2013 Sustainable Industries stopped publishing under its masthead.<ref>"[https://twitter.com/sustainablemag/status/414167450356170753 Farewell Transmission]" Twitter, Dec. 20, 2013</ref>

